nt|flash: aha - i'm reminded that Europe changed their convention card at the last minute|pg||
nt|flash: they were going to play 'European Std' (if such a thing exists), with 2/1 not GF|pg||
nt|flash: but changed to 2/1 GF|pg||
nt|flash: that left the biggest difference between the 2 cards as the upper limit on Negative Xs|pg||
nt|flash: 3@S for Europe; 7@H for USA|pg||
nt|flash: i was a bit surprised to see USA leaving no way out after a 2/1 - there are 2 versions of 'Eastern Scientific' which do allow it|pg||
nt|flash: using neither of those approaches puts an awful lot of hand-types into the 1NT response|pg||
nt|othered1: Individual format's best feature is that it lets you see how great players handles situations that in their preferred tight partnerships would be handled through agreements.  Not ...|pg||
nt|othered1: sure we've seen all that much along those lines.|pg||
nt|flash: the 2 approaches are to make a repeat of the 2/1 suit NF after a non-forward-going rebid|pg||
nt|flash: and to play the Jump Shift down (3@C over 1@S, for example) as natural and invitational|pg||
nt|flash: once you've removed the single-suit invitational hands from the 1NT response, it's much easier to distinguish among hand-types|pg||
nt|flash: any other questions?|pg||
nt|haans: score now?|pg||
nt|othered1: Don't some decent 2/1 pairs also make exceptions for some auctions that start 1@D -2@C, or even 1@S-2@H?|pg||
